"Using Thinking Routines in Emergency Remote Teaching (ERT) times üí≠","3135","<h2>How to use Thinking Routines in Emergency Remote Teaching (ERT) times?</h2>
Suddenly we were put behind the screen. We have desperately tried to find a way to engage students in our emergency remote classes but have realised we are back to stage one and have become teacher centered again. This can easily happen. Remember, it was not planned for. So, it does require creative problem solving. <em>Which platform should I use? Will it be synchronous or asynchronous? How will I <a href=""https://sphereinternationalschool.com.br/blog/2020/04/06/avaliacao-a-distancia/"" target=""_blank"" rel=""noopener noreferrer"">evaluate</a>? How do I know students are there and actually learning?</em>

This specific article is to encourage teachers to take a good look at thinking routines during these ERT classes and put them into practice to enhance student‚Äôs participation and engagement. Although thinking routines might seem like techniques that can only be used in face to face interactions, they work fantastically in live sessions with students on an online environment. Using thinking routines together with other collaborative platforms will help our classes become more student centered, fun and encouraging students to dig deeper into their own thoughts regarding the topics and themes you are proposing.
<h2><strong>What are thinking routines?</strong></h2>
Routines are part of our life. As from a very young age, we have routines, sometimes imposed by our parents and teachers and sometimes we impose them on ourselves. Some people say that people who stick to routines are better organised and productive than people who do not have a set regular plan.

Teachers have routines in their face to face classrooms, which are essential techniques to make sure our goals are accomplished and that our classroom management skills are put into practice. We need students to be engaged and active.

Thinking routines are techniques we apply to make our students better thinkers. Much has been said and talked about creative thinking and the importance of critical thinking in the classroom. But how do we teach that to students? Are there steps? Techniques?

Project Zero came up with steps to encourage students to make thinking a habit. They organised thinking skills into different categories to encourage students to analyse, question, observe, make analogies, critic, connect and many others. What is great about these routines is that they can be applied to any context, any subject and used for all ages. Not only pre-schoolers, but high school students benefit from these routines. To be honest, the earlier we start, the better, so students learn to observe their own thinking patterns from a very young age.

As the thinking routines are a short set of questions, they are easily applied and practical. They do not take up a lot of time and can be used with individual students or large groups. As Project Zero affirm ‚ÄúIt is the simplicity of the thinking routines that make them easy to use‚Äù. Understanding the routines and engaging students in them during this ERT period will boost your live sessions and engage your students deeper into the classes. You will find that students will become more active and participant in classes. Using collaborative platforms such as Padlet and online mind maps so students can together build on their different ideas will bring a whole new perspective and engagement for your classes.

<img src=""https://sphereinternationalschool.com.br/wp-content/uploads/2020/05/Padlet-dos-alunos-Y4-1024x453.png"" sizes=""(max-width: 800px) 100vw, 800px"" srcset=""https://sphereinternationalschool.com.br/wp-content/uploads/2020/05/Padlet-dos-alunos-Y4-1024x453.png 1024w, https://sphereinternationalschool.com.br/wp-content/uploads/2020/05/Padlet-dos-alunos-Y4-300x133.png 300w, https://sphereinternationalschool.com.br/wp-content/uploads/2020/05/Padlet-dos-alunos-Y4-768x340.png 768w, https://sphereinternationalschool.com.br/wp-content/uploads/2020/05/Padlet-dos-alunos-Y4.png 1294w"" alt=""Padlet dos alunos Y4"" width=""800"" height=""354"" />
<p id=""tw-target-text"" dir=""ltr"" data-placeholder=""Tradu√ß√£o"">Quarantine padlet produced by Sphere's Y4 students.</p>
For example, as we are living a very controversial moment where some people do not believe in social distancing and some are all for it, we can use the thinking routine ‚Äúcircle of viewpoints‚Äù which is a routine for exploring diverse perspectives. Encouraging students to follow the steps of the routine:
<ol>
 	<li><strong>I am thinking of</strong>¬†...¬†the topic...¬†<strong>From the point of view of</strong>¬†... the viewpoint you've chosen</li>
 	<li><strong>I think</strong>¬†...¬†describe the topic from your viewpoint. Be an actor - take on the character of your viewpoint</li>
 	<li><strong>A question I have from this viewpoint is¬†</strong>... ask a question from this viewpoint</li>
</ol>
http://www.visiblethinkingpz.org/VisibleThinking_html_files/03_ThinkingRoutines/03e_FairnessRoutines/CircleViewpoints/CircleViewpoints_Routine.html

Following the steps is crucial for students to understand how they reach the ultimate goal of the task. The article is mainly to remind teachers that the thinking routines should not be forgotten during these emergency times and can definitely aid teachers at making sure their classes are less teacher centered while in the ERT period.

And while I was writing this article, Project Zero published a new series of thinking routines specially for ERT. So now, we definitely have no reason not to use them. Check them out <a href=""https://pz.harvard.edu/at-home-with-pz"" target=""_blank"" rel=""noopener noreferrer"">here.</a>

The other thinking routines from Project Zero can be found <a href=""https://pz.harvard.edu/projects/visible-thinking"" target=""_blank"" rel=""noopener noreferrer"">here.</a>",,"2020-05-27 14:28:06","thinking-routines","paula.heleno","publish","https://sphereinternationalschool.com.br/wp-content/uploads/2020/05/IMG_9123.jpg",,"open","open","Educa√ß√£o,Metodologia",,,"-1|-1|large","Routines are part of our life.  But how do we teach thinking routines to students? Are there steps? Techniques?",,"off","https://sphereinternationalschool.com.br/wp-content/uploads/2020/05/IMG_9403-scaled.jpg","3114","play",,"Thinking Routines","1","thinking-routines","44","article","index","77","BlogPosting","Array","5","1","Organization","5","1",,"offline","Person","5","1","Event","on","custom","MusicGroup",,"on","5","1","SingleField","5","1","5","bottom","[rank_math_review_snippet]","1","[rank_math_rich_snippet]","5","1","Using Thinking Routines in Emergency Remote Teaching","summary_large_image","off","play","on"
"Pessoas em primeiro lugar: a educa√ß√£o na pandemia üôã‚Äç‚ôÄÔ∏è üôã‚Äç‚ôÇÔ∏è","3143","<h2>Perguntas centrais para educadores na pandemia</h2>		
		<p style=""text-align: right;"">Sara Vogel</p>
<p>No texto dessa semana, compartilhamos tr√™s perguntas essenciais propostas pela Dra. Sara Vogel, que foi palestrante no Sphere International Seminar de 2019.</p>
<p>Momento dif√≠cil de ensinar e aprender.</p>
<p>Com a propaga√ß√£o do coronav√≠rus COVID-19 pelo mundo, cursos universit√°rios e escolas de ensino fundamental e m√©dio passaram a operar on-line para ajudar as fam√≠lias a aderirem √†s pol√≠ticas de distanciamento social. V√°rios meses depois, algumas regi√µes e na√ß√µes come√ßaram a flexibilizar as restri√ß√µes. No entanto, √© prov√°vel que, por muito tempo, a escola n√£o volte a ser como antes da pandemia - ou mesmo nunca mais.</p>
<p>Como pesquisadora em educa√ß√£o na cidade de Nova York, trabalhando em projetos em colabora√ß√£o com professores de nossas escolas p√∫blicas, percebi que as experi√™ncias das pessoas com ""escola"" variam muito. Alguns estudantes t√™m acesso imediato a ferramentas de tecnologia e banda larga, e outros n√£o. Alguns se sentem estressados e outros entediados. Alguns ficam doentes, outros n√£o.</p>
<p>Com essa desigualdade e diversidade de experi√™ncias em mente, proponho tr√™s perguntas centrais que todos os educadores - independentemente da situa√ß√£o e localiza√ß√£o - poderiam e talvez devessem estar se perguntando e usando para orientar sua pr√°tica.</p>		
										<img width=""600"" height=""200"" src=""https://sphereinternationalschool.com.br/wp-content/uploads/2020/06/Como-estou-me-sentindo.png"" alt="""" srcset=""https://sphereinternationalschool.com.br/wp-content/uploads/2020/06/Como-estou-me-sentindo.png 600w, https://sphereinternationalschool.com.br/wp-content/uploads/2020/06/Como-estou-me-sentindo-300x100.png 300w"" sizes=""(max-width: 600px) 100vw, 600px"" />											
		<p>Meu colega, Dr. Christopher Hoadley, da Universidade de Nova York, chamou a aten√ß√£o da nossa equipe de projeto para um post da Professora Vanessa Dennen (Dennen, 2020). A Professora Dennen oferece um mantra simples que pode ajudar a todos n√≥s a estabelecer prioridades durante esses tempos: <b>primeiro as pessoas; conte√∫do segundo; terceiro a tecnologia.</b></p>		
										<img width=""800"" height=""695"" src=""https://sphereinternationalschool.com.br/wp-content/uploads/2020/06/how-are-you-feeling.jpg"" alt="""" srcset=""https://sphereinternationalschool.com.br/wp-content/uploads/2020/06/how-are-you-feeling.jpg 1379w, https://sphereinternationalschool.com.br/wp-content/uploads/2020/06/how-are-you-feeling-300x261.jpg 300w, https://sphereinternationalschool.com.br/wp-content/uploads/2020/06/how-are-you-feeling-1024x890.jpg 1024w, https://sphereinternationalschool.com.br/wp-content/uploads/2020/06/how-are-you-feeling-768x667.jpg 768w"" sizes=""(max-width: 800px) 100vw, 800px"" />											
		<p style=""margin: 12.0pt 0cm 12.0pt 0cm;"">Entendi que isso significa que, antes que os educadores possam atender √†s necessidades de seus alunos, eles devem cuidar de si mesmos - garantir que eles e suas fam√≠lias estejam fisicamente e mentalmente saud√°veis. Esta n√£o √© uma tarefa f√°cil. As pessoas enfrentam lutas diferentes, dependendo de suas circunst√¢ncias econ√¥micas e sociais e dos tipos de apoio oferecidos pelos governos locais e nacionais (Goldstein et al., 2020).¬†</p>		
										<img width=""600"" height=""200"" src=""https://sphereinternationalschool.com.br/wp-content/uploads/2020/06/quais-s√£o-suas-realidades.png"" alt="""" srcset=""https://sphereinternationalschool.com.br/wp-content/uploads/2020/06/quais-s√£o-suas-realidades.png 600w, https://sphereinternationalschool.com.br/wp-content/uploads/2020/06/quais-s√£o-suas-realidades-300x100.png 300w"" sizes=""(max-width: 600px) 100vw, 600px"" />											
		<p>√Ä medida em que os professores cuidam de sua pr√≥pria sa√∫de e da sa√∫de de suas fam√≠lias, as orienta√ß√µes de ""People First"" de Dennen tamb√©m devem inspir√°-los a fazer um balan√ßo das realidades dos alunos. Onde est√£o os alunos e com quem? Todos os membros em casa est√£o saud√°veis? Quais s√£o as emo√ß√µes e capacidades de seus alunos para aprender neste momento? Qual a participa√ß√£o ativa dos pais na aprendizagem dos alunos?¬†</p><p style=""margin: 12.0pt 0cm 12.0pt 0cm;"">Tamb√©m seria √∫til aprender sobre as pr√°ticas n√£o digitais que acontecem em casa - as fam√≠lias est√£o cozinhando juntas? Brincando com jogos e brinquedos? Fazendo arte ou m√∫sica? Indo para caminhadas na natureza? O conhecimento dessas informa√ß√µes sobre os <i>‚Äúfunds of knowledge‚Äù (patrim√¥nios culturais) </i>dos alunos (Moll et al., 2005) pode ajudar os professores a projetar experi√™ncias de aprendizado que se conectar√£o com as realidades presentes dos alunos.</p>		
										<img width=""800"" height=""627"" src=""https://sphereinternationalschool.com.br/wp-content/uploads/2020/06/578902-1024x803.jpg"" alt="""" srcset=""https://sphereinternationalschool.com.br/wp-content/uploads/2020/06/578902-1024x803.jpg 1024w, https://sphereinternationalschool.com.br/wp-content/uploads/2020/06/578902-300x235.jpg 300w, https://sphereinternationalschool.com.br/wp-content/uploads/2020/06/578902-768x602.jpg 768w, https://sphereinternationalschool.com.br/wp-content/uploads/2020/06/578902.jpg 1240w"" sizes=""(max-width: 800px) 100vw, 800px"" />											
										<img width=""600"" height=""200"" src=""https://sphereinternationalschool.com.br/wp-content/uploads/2020/06/Pra-que-serve-a-escola.png"" alt="""" srcset=""https://sphereinternationalschool.com.br/wp-content/uploads/2020/06/Pra-que-serve-a-escola.png 600w, https://sphereinternationalschool.com.br/wp-content/uploads/2020/06/Pra-que-serve-a-escola-300x100.png 300w"" sizes=""(max-width: 600px) 100vw, 600px"" />											
										<img width=""626"" height=""500"" src=""https://sphereinternationalschool.com.br/wp-content/uploads/2020/06/Aluno-tendo-aulas-online.jpg"" alt="""" srcset=""https://sphereinternationalschool.com.br/wp-content/uploads/2020/06/Aluno-tendo-aulas-online.jpg 626w, https://sphereinternationalschool.com.br/wp-content/uploads/2020/06/Aluno-tendo-aulas-online-300x240.jpg 300w"" sizes=""(max-width: 626px) 100vw, 626px"" />											
		<p style=""margin: 12.0pt 0cm 12.0pt 0cm;"">Essa pandemia reacende debates seculares sobre os prop√≥sitos da escola. Hoje, as crian√ßas precisam compreender o contexto para se engajar e gerenciar seu tempo em tarefas escolares. Se eles n√£o veem a relev√¢ncia ou import√¢ncia dessas tarefas, por que faz√™-las? H√° muitas outras coisas conectadas aos seus interesses nos dispositivos eletr√¥nicos e nos espa√ßos da casa.</p><p>Os educadores devem se perguntar sobre seu papel e o papel da ""escola"" nesta crise. Talvez as escolas e os professores considerem como prioridade oferecer aos alunos uma rotina est√°vel e cuidado atento. Se for esse o caso, a pr√°tica deve refletir esse valor - talvez as escolas tenham tempo para os professores acompanharem os alunos em v√≠deoconfer√™ncias durante a semana ou come√ßarem todos os dias com uma ""verifica√ß√£o de temperatura"" emocional durante um bate-papo por v√≠deo. Talvez os educadores se considerem mentores de alunos, especialmente dos mais velhos. Eles podem aprender sobre o que os alunos gostam de fazer em casa e ajud√°-los a aprofundar e expandir essas paix√µes e interesses. A comunidade do¬†<a href=""https://clalliance.org/about-connected-learning/"" target=""_blank"" rel=""noopener noreferrer"">Connected Learning</a>¬†(Dyson &amp; Larson, 2019) e muitos outros nos lembram que o aprendizado pode acontecer a qualquer hora e em qualquer lugar. O <em>professor como mentor</em> pode direcionar os alunos para recursos relevantes e comunidades on-line seguras - por exemplo, a comunidade de escritores de <em>fan-fiction</em> do Wattpad (<a href=""http://wattpad.com/"" target=""_blank"" rel=""noopener noreferrer"">http://wattpad.com/</a>) ou a comunidade Scratch para criar e compartilhar hist√≥rias e jogos digitais (<a href=""http://scratch.mit.edu"" target=""_blank"" rel=""noopener noreferrer"">http://scratch.mit.edu</a>) ou um canal do YouTube para atividades f√≠sicas, culin√°ria ou arte - depois solicitar que os alunos justif